{
  "result": "Some mornings feel like hidden rooms behind the regular corridors of time, liminal alcoves where nothing demands immediate resolution. I like to wake before the neighborhood stirs, listening to the faint transformer hum outside my window while the sky negotiates its transition from graphite to diluted silver. In that interval, responsibilities seem to loosen their knots. Projects and deadlines still exist, yet their outlines soften, as though seen through fogged glass. It is tempting to open the laptop, check messages, begin the churn, but instead I brew a slow cup of tea and watch the steam braiding upward.\n\nThese minutes allow ideas to drift without the expectation of productivity. I scribble half sentences in a notebook, fragmentary images that might later stitch themselves into essays, stories, or plans. Sometimes nothing usable appears. That is acceptable; the practice itself feels like tending a garden, trusting that some seeds stay dormant until a future season. The world offers so many measurements\u2014word counts, revenue charts, social engagements\u2014that the unmeasured spaces become precious. They remind me that attention can be devoted to the quality of experience rather than the quantity of output.\n\nEventually the streets awaken. Garbage trucks clatter, dogs tug leashes, phones buzz. I join the day with more steadiness, because I carried the silence within me for a while. Like a talisman in a pocket, it grounds me when the hours accelerate. Liminal mornings are easily overlooked, yet they may be where our truest selves stretch, yawn, and remember they are alive.",
